# acronym-cli

A command-line tool to manage and lookup acronyms.

## Features

- Lookup acronyms
- Add new acronyms (interactive prompts)
- Delete acronyms (with confirmation)
- List all acronyms
- Shell autocomplete support (Bash, Zsh, Fish)

---

## Install

### Recommended: pipx

Install in an isolated environment for safety:

```bash
pipx install git+https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/acronym-cli.git
```

### Alternatively: pip

pip install git+https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/acronym-cli.git

## Usage

### Lookup an acronym

```acronym API
```

Displays the full name and description of the acronym.
Add a new acronym

```acronym add API
```
    Prompts for full name and description if not provided with --full-name or --description

    Confirms before overwriting if the acronym already exists

Example with options:
```
acronym add API --full-name "Application Programming Interface" --description "A set of rules that allow software to communicate"
```
### Delete an acronym

acronym delete API

    Asks for confirmation before deleting

### List all acronyms

```acronym --list
```
Displays a table of all stored acronyms with their full name and description.
Using a custom data file

By default, acronyms are stored in acronyms.yaml in the current directory.

acronym -f my_acronyms.yaml API
acronym add HTTP --full-name "Hypertext Transfer Protocol" --description "Web protocol" -f my_acronyms.yaml

```Shell autocomplete
```
Enable shell autocomplete for faster usage.
### Bash

```eval "$(_ACRONYM_COMPLETE=source_bash acronym)"
```
### Zsh

```eval "$(_ACRONYM_COMPLETE=source_zsh acronym)"
```
### Fish
```
eval (env _ACRONYM_COMPLETE=source_fish acronym)
```
Add the relevant line to your shell configuration file (.bashrc, .zshrc, config.fish) to persist.
## Example workflow

# Add a new acronym
acronym add HTTP

### Lookup
acronym HTTP

### List all acronyms
acronym --list

### Delete an acronym
acronym delete HTTP

